obo:ECO_0007719  a  owl:Class .

lego:evidence  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

gomodel:SYNGO_4739  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1: Western blots of rat forebrain synaptic membranes indicated that the PSD-95 (DLG4) antibodies recognized a doublet band, at a molecular weight of about 95 kDa, under control conditions (Fig. 1). Purified calpain I (CAPN1, calpain 1, μ-calpain) treatment resulted in a decrease in native PSD-95 protein, and in the formation of two prominent truncation products, two doublet bands migrating at 50 and 36 kDa, respectively. This effect was completely blocked by calpain inhibitors, either calpain inhibitor III (100 μM) or leupeptin (100 μM).\n\nFigure 3; Effect of calcium treatment of frozen-thawed brain sections and NMDA treatment of organotypic hippocampal cultures on PSD-95. The proteolytic pattern was identical to that obtained with calpain I digestion of synaptic membranes, with clear identification of the 50 and 36 kDa bands. To further verify that calpains, but not other proteases, were responsible for the calcium-induced degradation of PSD-95, a series of protease inhibitors were added to the incubation buffer. Calcium-dependent degradation of PSD-95 was not affected by the serine protease inhibitor, aprotinin (50 μM), but was totally blocked by EGTA (2 mM) and two calpain inhibitors, calpain inhibitor III (100 μM) and leupeptin (100 μM). Thus, calcium-mediated PSD-95 degradation in frozen-thawed rat brain sections is due to calpain activation. Experimental description: \"Fig. 1. PSD-95 degradation by calpain in rat forebrain synaptic membranes\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" ;
        dc:date           "2022-08-02" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4739" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

